  <section|Truth Valuation赋值/真值指派>

  <subsection|Definition>

  To interpret a formula, we have to give meanings to the propositional variables and the connectives.

  <\definition>
    \;

    A truth valuation is a function v : Atom(<math|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>>) \<rightarrow\> {0, 1}.\ 

    For p \<in\> Atom(<math|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>>), we use v(p) or <math|p<rsup|v>> to denote the truth value of p under the truth valuation v, <math|p<rsup|v>> \<in\> {0, 1}
  </definition>

  \;

  Fix a truth valuation v. Every formula A has a value under v, denoted as A^v, can berecursively defined as:

  <\definition>
    \;

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|p<rsup|v>\<in\><around*|{|0,1|}>>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|\<neg\>A|)>=<choice|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1,if A<rsup|v>=0>>|<row|<cell|0,if A<rsup|v>=1>>>>>>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|A\<wedge\>B|)><rsup|v>=<choice|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1,if A<rsup|v>=1 and B<rsup|v>=1>>|<row|<cell|0,else>>>>>>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|A\<vee\>B|)><rsup|v>=<choice|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1,if A<rsup|v>=1 or B<rsup|v>=1>>|<row|<cell|0,else>>>>>>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|A\<rightarrow\>B|)><rsup|v>=<choice|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1,if A<rsup|v>=0 or A<rsup|v>=1 and B<rsup|v>=1>>|<row|<cell|0,else>>>>>>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|A\<leftrightarrow\>B|)><rsup|v>=<choice|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1,if A<rsup|v>= B<rsup|v>>>|<row|<cell|0,else>>>>>>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>
  </definition>

  <subsection|合式公式的确定性>

  <\theorem>
    \;

    Fix a truth valuation v. Every formula \<alpha\> \<in\> Form(<math|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>>) has a value <math|\<alpha\><rsup|v>> in {0, 1}.
  </theorem>

  <subsection|一些称谓>

  Let A<math|\<in\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>>

  <\itemize-dot>
    <item>If for every truth valuation v, A^v = 1, then A is tautology (永真式或重言式)

    <item>If for every truth valuation v, A^v = 0, then A is contradiction (永假式或矛盾式)\ 

    <item>If there exists a truth value v such that A^v = 1, then A satisfiable (可满足的)
  </itemize-dot>

  \;

  <section|How to determin the semantic properties?>

  <subsection|Institution?>

  <subsection|Valuation Tree>

  <with|par-mode|center|<image|<tuple|<#>|png>|0.8par|||>>

  <subsection|Prove by Contradiction>

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|>|<cell|((A \<rightarrow\> (B \<rightarrow\> C)) \<rightarrow\> ((A \<rightarrow\> B) \<rightarrow\> (A \<rightarrow\> C)))>>>>
  </align>

  Prove that the formula below is tautology

  <\proof>
    \;

    If it is not tautology:

    there exist a Valuation that both

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|(A \<rightarrow\> (B \<rightarrow\> C))<rsup|v>=1>|<cell|<eq-number>>>|<row|<cell|((A \<rightarrow\> B) \<rightarrow\> (A \<rightarrow\> C))<rsup|v>=0>|<cell|<eq-number>>>>>
    </align>

    \;

    For (2);

    there exist a Valuation that both

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|A\<rightarrow\>B|)><rsup|v>=1>|<cell|<eq-number>>>|<row|<cell|<around*|(|A\<rightarrow\>C|)><rsup|v>=0>|<cell|<eq-number>>>>>
    </align>

    For (4):

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|A<rsup|v>=1,C<rsup|v>=0>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>

    bring it back to (3):

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|B<rsup|v>=1>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>

    but for (1):

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|1\<rightarrow\><around*|(|1\<rightarrow\>0|)>|)><rsup|v>=<around*|(|1\<rightarrow\>0|)><rsup|v>=0\<neq\>1>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>

    that makes a contradictory.

    \;
  </proof>

  <subsection|Prove Using Truth Table>

  <\with|par-mode|center>
    <image|<tuple|<#>|png>|0.8par|||>
  </with>

  <subsection|Application>

  程序编辑器：Finding live/dead code.

  <section|Logical Equivalence>

  <subsection|Definition>

  <\definition>
    Logical Equivalence

    Two formulas A and B are logically equivalent if and only if they have the same value under any valuation. We denote it as <math|A\<equiv\>B>.
  </definition>

  有三个等价命题：

  \<bullet\> A^v = B^v for every truth valuation v.\ 

  \<bullet\> A and B must have the same final column in their truth tables.\ 

  \<bullet\> A \<leftrightarrow\> B is a tautology.

  \;

  <subsection|Logical \ Identities>

